(42, 23, 50, 43, 19, 38, 42, 'a good man, and a just', 'Joseph''s Role in Burial', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph''s character as a good man and his involvement in the burial of Jesus. Luke introduces Joseph as a just man, while John details his actions in taking Jesus'' body, highlighting his courage and devotion.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 50, 44, 10, 22, 22, NULL, 'Character of Just Men', 'This connection highlights the characterization of both Joseph and Cornelius as ''just'' men, emphasizing their moral integrity and favorable standing within their communities. Both passages present these figures as exemplary individuals who are recognized for their goodness and righteousness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 50, 44, 11, 24, 24, 'good man', 'Connection of Goodness in Characters', 'Both passages emphasize the quality of being a ''good man.'' Joseph is described as a good and just man, while Barnabas is noted as a good man full of faith. This connection highlights the importance of moral character in both figures.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 50, 40, 27, 57, 61, 'a good man, and a just', 'Joseph''s Role in Jesus'' Burial', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph''s character as a good and just man who took action after Jesus'' death. In Luke, he is introduced as a counsellor, while Matthew details his role in requesting Jesus'' body and providing a tomb for burial.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 50, 41, 15, 42, 47, 'a counsellor; and he was a good man, and a just', 'Joseph of Arimathea''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph as a counsellor who took action after Jesus'' death. Luke describes him as a good and just man, while Mark details his bold request for Jesus'' body, highlighting his honorable character.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 50, 42, 2, 25, 25, 'just', 'Righteousness of Key Figures', 'Both passages emphasize the righteousness of their subjects, describing Joseph as ''a good man, and a just'' and Simeon as ''just and devout.'' This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in the context of significant figures in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 42, 2, 25, 25, NULL, 'Waiting for God''s Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of waiting for God''s promise. In Luke 23:51, Joseph of Arimathea is described as ''waiting for the kingdom of God,'' while Simeon in Luke 2:25 is ''waiting for the consolation of Israel.'' This connection highlights a shared anticipation of divine fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 42, 2, 38, 38, 'waited for the kingdom of God', 'Expectation of Redemption', 'Both passages emphasize a longing for God''s kingdom and redemption. Joseph of Arimathea ''waited for the kingdom of God,'' while those in Jerusalem looked for ''redemption.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 1, 37, 21, 22, 'who also himself waited for the kingdom of God', 'Deliverance and Waiting for Redemption', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for deliverance. In both passages, there is a focus on individuals who seek to save others from harm, with Joseph''s brothers intending to harm him and Reuben advocating for his safety, paralleling Joseph of Arimathea''s anticipation of the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 1, 42, 21, 22, 'waited for the kingdom of God', 'Guilt and Waiting for Redemption', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for redemption amidst guilt. In Luke, Joseph of Arimathea waits for the kingdom of God, while in Genesis, the brothers express guilt over their actions against Joseph, indicating a longing for resolution.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 23, 8, 12, 12, 'waited for the kingdom of God', 'Waiting for God''s Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for God''s kingdom in both passages. In Luke, Joseph of Arimathea is described as one who ''waited for the kingdom of God,'' while Isaiah encourages not to fear the confederacies of men, suggesting a focus on divine hope and assurance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 41, 15, 43, 43, 'who also himself waited for the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Joseph of Arimathea', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph of Arimathea''s role as a member of the council who awaited the kingdom of God. This shared description highlights his honorable character and his actions regarding Jesus'' body.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 51, 2, 23, 2, 2, '(The same had not consented to the counsel and deed of them;)', 'Resistance to Evil Counsel', 'This connection highlights the theme of standing against evil influences. In Luke 23:51, Joseph of Arimathea did not consent to the counsel of others, paralleling Exodus 23:2''s admonition against following a multitude to do evil.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 52, 43, 19, 38, 42, 'begged the body of Jesus', 'Joseph of Arimathea''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph of Arimathea''s action of taking the body of Jesus. The SOURCE verse mentions his request to Pilate, while the TARGET passage provides additional details about his actions and motivations.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 53, 40, 27, 59, 60, 'wrapped it in linen', 'Burial of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of wrapping Jesus'' body in linen and laying it in a tomb hewn from stone. This connection highlights the details of Jesus'' burial, underscoring the significance of the tomb being new and unused.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 53, 23, 53, 9, 9, 'laid it in a sepulchre', 'Connection of Burial Context', 'This connection highlights the burial of Jesus in a rich man''s tomb, as noted in both passages. Isaiah 53:9 mentions making his grave with the wicked and the rich, which aligns with Luke 23:53''s description of the sepulchre that was hewn in stone.', 'prophecy', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 53, 41, 15, 46, 46, NULL, 'Burial of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking Jesus down from the cross and laying him in a sepulchre hewn from stone. They describe similar actions regarding the burial process, highlighting the use of linen and the specific type of tomb.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 54, 40, 27, 62, 62, NULL, 'Preparation Day Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the ''day of the preparation'' in the timeline of events surrounding Jesus'' crucifixion. This connection highlights the transition from the preparation day to the Sabbath and the subsequent actions of the chief priests and Pharisees.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 54, 43, 19, 31, 31, 'the preparation', 'Connection of Preparation and Sabbath', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of ''the preparation'' and the approaching ''sabbath.'' This connection highlights the urgency of the actions taken regarding the bodies on the crosses to ensure they were removed before the sabbath began.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 54, 41, 15, 42, 42, 'the preparation', 'Preparation Day References', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''preparation'' as it relates to the day before the Sabbath. This connection highlights the timing of events surrounding the crucifixion and burial of Jesus.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 54, 43, 19, 14, 14, 'the preparation', 'Preparation Day Connection', 'Both passages emphasize ''the preparation'' before significant events. Luke refers to the preparation before the Sabbath, while John specifies it as the preparation of the Passover, highlighting the importance of timing in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 54, 43, 19, 42, 42, 'preparation', 'Preparation Day Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the preparation day leading up to the Sabbath. They highlight the urgency surrounding Jesus'' burial due to the impending Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 55, 42, 23, 49, 49, NULL, 'Women Following Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of the women who followed Jesus from Galilee. They are depicted as witnesses to significant events surrounding his crucifixion and burial.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 55, 40, 27, 61, 61, 'the women also, which came with him', 'Women at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of women at the sepulchre, highlighting their role in witnessing the burial of Jesus. The mention of Mary Magdalene and the other Mary in Matthew connects to the women from Galilee in Luke.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 55, 41, 15, 47, 47, NULL, 'Women Observing the Burial', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of women who witnessed the burial of Jesus. They highlight the act of observing where his body was laid, connecting the accounts of Luke and Mark.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 55, 42, 8, 2, 2, 'which came with him from Galilee', 'Women Following Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the role of women in Jesus'' ministry. In Luke 8:2, women are highlighted for their healing, while in Luke 23:55, they are depicted as followers witnessing his burial.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 56, 42, 24, 1, 1, 'prepared spices and ointments', 'Preparation and Action Sequence', 'This connection highlights the sequence of events where the women prepared spices and ointments in Luke 23:56 and then acted on that preparation by bringing them to the sepulchre in Luke 24:1. Both passages emphasize the continuity of their actions from preparation to execution.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 56, 41, 16, 1, 1, 'prepared spices and ointments', 'Preparation for Anointing Jesus', 'This connection highlights the actions of the women preparing spices for Jesus'' anointing. Both passages emphasize the significance of the sabbath and the subsequent act of anointing after it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 56, 5, 5, 14, 14, 'rested the sabbath day according to the commandment', 'Sabbath Observance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of resting on the Sabbath. Luke 23:56 highlights the observance of the Sabbath after Jesus'' crucifixion, aligning with Deuteronomy 5:14''s commandment to refrain from work on that day.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
